  <text>
    The alarms won't stop.

    Red lights pulse through the cargo bay as the shuttle shudders, atmosphere tearing at the hull. I'm strapped into the jumpseat, cargo containers rattling in their restraints around me. We're coming in wrong—too steep, too fast, the angle all kinds of bad.

    "Nav system offline," the automated voice announces, flat and unhelpful.

    Then life support fails.

    Then the stabilizers.

    The shuttle pitches sideways and I slam against the straps hard enough to bruise. My ribs scream. Can't breathe. Can't reach the cockpit—it's through a sealed door and I'm cargo, just cargo, riding in back while the pilots up front try to save us and probably can't.

    Heat. The hull's burning up. Metal shrieks. Something tears loose and crashes into the wall next to my head.

    I'm going to die.

    The thought is crystal clear, clinical, completely certain. This is it. Twenty-four years old and I'm going to die in the back of a cargo shuttle, strapped in like freight, while the whole thing comes apart around me.

    Impact hits like a wall.

    Everything—

    Silence.

    Darkness.

    Nothing.
  </text>
  <summary>
    Kira's shuttle crashes while entering an unknown planet's atmosphere. System failures cascade—navigation, life support, stabilizers all fail. Kira, trapped in the cargo bay and unable to reach the pilots, experiences the terror of inevitable impact before everything goes dark.
  </summary>
  <leaves-off>
    Silence and darkness. Kira is unconscious after the violent impact, fate unknown. Next passage will show her waking up in the wreckage.
  </leaves-off>
